posts.com: perfect pitch is a stupid name for it, what it means is absolute instead of relative pitch recognition, and it is pretty much completely useless for musical purposes

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
Perfect pitch means that with no reference, you can tell what a given pitch is (or, alternately, produce it)

Depending on the person it might be more or less precise, or some might be able to pick out the note from very "unmusical" sounds like train engines or hammer hits or whatever while someone else wouldn't be able to, but the common and most important characteristic is the "no reference" thing.

Relative pitch is just the ability to, if you know a specific note, relate any following note back to that first note. If I give you a C and then play another note on another instrument, relative pitch is the ability to say "oh yeah that's an F# because it's clearly a tritone up from that first note which I know is C".

Perfect pitch does not imply any musical knowledge, just the ability to tell pitches without reference. Some people develop perfect pitch without knowing musical notation or note names, so for them they'll hear a sound and just conceptualise it as matching that specific key on their parents' old piano they grew up with, for or something like that. Of course it usually takes trying to play music to even realise you have perfect pitch.

A piano teacher of mine once told me that he noticed his students with perfect pitch would often tend to in fact have kind of a worse knowledge of musical theory, scales, key signatures, modes and all than his students with good relative pitch, basically because they either didn't need it or had to retro-engineer it.

Like if you give two notes that clearly sound like a major third to them, they wouldn't think "oh that's a major third", they'd think "oh that's an A and a C#", and then would need the extra step to think "C# up from A, that's four semitones, so it's a major third".

Regardless of what you have, learning interval recognition and just generally practicing ear training by learning songs and whatnot never hurts.

It's a bit more nuanced than that, I can do the isolated note thing too just from having trained relative pitch and being able to sing a couple notes in my head from memory very reliably. This is the 'muscle-memory' type pitch that OP was describing. If you have good relative pitch and some pitch memory (remembering the first note of a melody you know well for example) it can start to look like perfect pitch but it really isn't. Perfect pitch requires no such effort and isn't made more or less difficult by being in the context of key centers with lots of sharps or flats. It 's as instantaneous and automatic as identifying an apple as red.

>>114464997
desu you really have to know how to play the drums to program drums that sound real.

But If you just want less robotic sounding, it’s all about syncopation. Syncopation makes the rhythm. You can have the most robotic on-the-grid kick, snare and hats, but when you add another perc sound that accents an off beat in one of the measures, it fixes it and sounds human. The breakbeat sample on top works because it has syncopation in the pattern.

And to preemptively clarify what I mean by accenting the off beats. It’s the extra kick drum hits just before the end of the phrase. It’s the extra snare hit before or after the 2s and 4s. It’s the Tom hit when every other perc is on a rest.

Good tune btw

>>114468807

My take on the matter:
I just did some heavy leads tone test on top of this Youtube heavy track https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UTPADCjSIcE

No mixing or processing involved, just pure sound of ZOOM DSP into CAB sims in DAW. It cuts right through the track. This unit is a digital signal processor, but it has a analog valve single tube for preamp stage for some gain saturation.

https://vocaroo.com/1aoJxs7V9i7N

Even though this unit is 30 years old, it is still better in "cutting through" any heavy distorted mix than even some of the NEURAL DSP sim stuff I have tried that use pure guitar signal without any analog stages before the DAW. And this is without any post-EQ or mixing.

Literally just get some old hardware, these units sell for about 100-120 dollars used, the avg. you would spend on some shitty Amp sim with 1000 features and they all sound mediocre and always require shit ton of mixing, EQ and fucking around. Everything else, IRs, Power Amp sims, can be found for free.

One piece of easy, cheap-as-free advice is to envision what a physical setup would be and think about how to recreate digitally. So, for example, if you had a plex turned to 11 you'd stick a sm57 in the sweet spot and a 121 in the middle maybe. Well, that would mean taking two copies of the same guitar wav with the same amp and cab sims and treating them different in terms of eq. You're not pushing real air against a Mic but you can bus both of those to a separate reverb channel and keep bringing it up in the mix a cunt hair at a time until it's Just barely audible.

lol this is the hard way to make a melody.

some people start here. or some people figure out major/minor scales modes etc and try to use those to make melodies.. but again it's too many notes in my opinion to easily make a good melody.

Simplify it down to the pentatonic scale OR a six note scale. By six note scale, I mean like the major scale with the fourth removed, or a minor scale without the 6th.
It helps if you can improvise around these scales too.
Most melodies are really simple and only use these notes.
Going up and down scales is a good way to make amateur sounding melodies. Leave some notes out, the ones that don't sound that good, just play the notes that sound good. Easy.

The Beach Boys Love You [Brother/Reprise, 1977]

Painfully crackpot and painfully sung, but also inspired, not least because it calls forth forbidden emotions. For a surrogate teenager to bare his growing pains so guilelessly was exciting, or at least charming; for an avowed adult to expose an almost childish naivete is embarrassing, but also cathartic; and for a rock and roll hero to compose a verbally and musically irresistible paean to Johnny Carson is an act of shamanism pure and simple. As with Wild Honey, the music sounds wrong in contradictory ways at first--both arty and cute, spare and smarmy--but on almost every cut it comes together soon enough; I am especially partial to the organ textures, and I find the absurd little astrology ditty, "Solar System," impossible to shake. As for the words, well, they're often pretty silly, but even (especially) when they're designed to appeal to whatever Brian imagines to be the rock audience they reveal a lot more about the artist than most lyrics do. And this artist is a very interesting case. A

You don't have to be super good at it. You just need to be able to lay out a 5x12 grid in your head. There's really nothing to teach on that. You just git gud by trying.

>>114487137
The first thing I learned to visualize was the order of notes down the strings. A#BC#D#EF#G#. To remember where the half steps aren't I first asked myself "why is it even like that", then I put the only answer I could come up with in my head.
>BeCausE Fuck
I just see that, with the BC and EF capitalized, and I instantly know there's no half steps in between them.
All I had to visualize was a word with some capitalized letters. If you want to become a visualization god you just have to think about stuff without having a physical model of it in front of you and gradually get more complex with it until you're playing chess and building model ships in your head.
It's not necessary for this though. If you can't see words in your head then just spell out the alphabet in your head without the crutch of singing it and then once the letters are clear start trying to see words. You'll get it quickly if you try. People think non visualizes are retarded but it's just that they don't practice it.

I just did some heavy leads tone test on top of this Youtube heavy track https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UTPADCjSIcE

No mixing or processing involved, just pure sound of ZOOM DSP into CAB sims in DAW. It cuts right through the track and mix. This unit is a digital signal processor, but it has a analog valve single tube for preamp stage for some gain saturation.

https://vocaroo.com/1aoJxs7V9i7N

Even though this unit is 30 years old, it is still better in "cutting through" any heavy distorted mix than even some of the NEURAL DSP sim stuff I have tried that use pure guitar signal without any analog stages before the DAW. And this is without any post-EQ or mixing. Literally just get some old hardware, these units sell for about 100-120 dollars used, the avg. you would spend on some shitty Amp sim with 1000 features and they all sound mediocre and always require shit ton of mixing, EQ and fucking around. Everything else, IRs, Power Amp sims, can be found for free.

I've hoarded certain gear that is still affordable (old rack preamps) because I've noticed that they go on sale less often (Ebay, Reverb) and when they do: someone has added like $100-200 to the price and other sellers follow the lead. In 5 years it will have like $700 added to avg. sell price. Decided few years ago that better to buy 5 units of the same thing for $500 than pay $2500 for it 5 years down the road. This stuff is mainly used for my bread and butter setup recording and the other units are literally for me just in case some of these breaks and they are sealed/stored away carefully. Maybe it's hoarder logic, but I calculated that if one unit on average lasts me ~15 years without breaking and I have spare parts these should last me a lifetime and 20 years from now who the fuck knows how absurd the prices of used market is when some of these 80s-90s units will be 50-60 years old.

posts.com:
hey guys I started playing guitar recently, just been learning some songs for about 30-45 minutes a day, maybe an hour total. I'm a complete beginner, does anyone have some resources to keep me progressing at a good rate?

Or should I just keep learning songs until I can move my fret hand around well before I get into memorizing chords and scales? Im still muting notes and not playing smoothly at all, especially transitioning between wildly different phrases

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114472786
The most efficient way would be sticking to a curriculum either something made by someone online (tons of youtube channels have series for free), paying for a tutor that will give you a plan of attack and correct poor technique or getting a good course book. Then learning songs on top of that after you do your daily homework. Having a tutor or doing a video course can help a lot because you can follow their technique like hand/wrist rather than trying to figure out how to get to the next string yourself.

Only learning songs you want to play is a valid strategy if that's what keeps you motivated but you'll run into roadblocks more often and when you get a bit better it can be hard to find specific songs to practice specific techniques you need to work on. As long as you're playing the song very slowly to make sure you know it instead of trying to brute force playing it at full speed. So you need to find a balance between staying motivated by playing what you want while keeping pace on improving so you don't get frustrated and give up.

Get an acoustic then, if you stick with it it'll make picking up electric later even easier since you're used to much heavier strings and you can't really hide poor technique on acoustic. Not sure what your budget is but the Epiphone J45 and Hummingbird are very very good acoustics if you can find one for less than $350, and the Yamaha (Yamaha FG800) and Ibanez (Ibanez AW54) entry level ones are very good too.

Good acoustics sometimes cost a little more than a good electric but you also don't need to buy an amp so it evens out. But I would recommend trying them out in a store to see what's comfortable if you can then you don't need to worry about things like adjusting the truss rod to start playing since a lot of them are shipped very slack.

>design a circuit for an overdrive guitar pedal, describe the components and how they connect, and then provide a list of the components, all through-hole so I can solder them easily

An overdrive guitar pedal circuit typically consists of several key components: a input buffer, an overdrive circuit, a tone control circuit, and an output buffer. These components are connected in a specific way to achieve the desired effect.

Here's a basic circuit diagram for an overdrive guitar pedal, with through-hole components:

Input buffer: This circuit amplifies the guitar's weak output signal to a level that can drive the rest of the pedal. It's often built around an op-amp IC, such as the LM741.
Overdrive circuit: This is the heart of the pedal, and it's where the guitar signal is distorted to produce the overdrive effect. A common choice is to use a diode clipping circuit, which uses diodes to clip the peaks of the incoming signal, creating a distorted sound. You can use 1n4148 diodes for this circuit.
Tone control circuit: This circuit allows the user to adjust the tone of the overdrive effect. A simple tone control circuit can be built around a potentiometer.
Output buffer: This circuit is used to drive the guitar amplifier or other pedal chain. This can be built around an op-amp IC, such as the LM741, as well.

Here is a list of the components you need and their function:

Input buffer
LM741 op-amp IC
10k resistor
100nF capacitor
Overdrive circuit
1n4148 diodes
10k resistor
100nF capacitor
Tone control circuit
10k potentiometer
Output buffer
LM741 op-amp IC
10k resistor
100nF capacitor

You should also have power supply components such as a 9V battery clip and an DC jack to connect a power supply.

>>114472630

>>114475434

It's extremely important for mixed meter, 4/4 alternating with 7/4 is a waaaay different length than 4/4 alternating with 7/8. Even without that it can be important for indicating feel, for example the idiot that said 3/4 and 6/8 sound the same is missing that 6/8 usually actually sounds like 2/4 with a triplet feel (and 12/8 is the compound equivalent of 4/4).

Plus when you're really cool you can learn about irrational time signatures and putting literally any number in the bottom. 5/7 for example would be taking a giant septuplet over a bar of 4/4 and replacing the last two notes with a sudden, very angular downbeat. Can lead to some really twisty and interesting riffs that basically nobody will figure out unless they see the sheet music and it's surprisingly easy to actually perform if you're on top of your basic tuplet timings.

The lyrics of the song tell the story of a man who is pretending to be a robot and singing in robotic language (domo arigato, mr roboto) as a way to conceal his true identity. He reveals that he is "not a robot without emotions," and that he has come to help others with their problems and to be free. The song is a commentary on the role of technology in society and the fear of losing our humanity in the face of rapid technological advancement. It's a unique blend of rock music, as well as futuristic, robotic elements.

What is 4chan?

4chan is a controversial and largely unmoderated online forum that is divided into various boards with their own specific content and guidelines. The website was created in 2003 by a 15-year-old boy named Christopher Poole, and it is known for its anonymity, which allows users to post messages without revealing their identity.

The site is known for its wide variety of content, including but not limited to, memes, anime, manga, politics, video games, music, technology, and adult content. Some of the boards are dedicated to specific topics such as /b/ (random) and /pol/ (politics).

4chan is known for its politically incorrect content, and it is often associated with the alt-right and white supremacists, it also has been the source of various cyberbullying, hate speech, and controversial content; Some of its users have been linked to various internet hoaxes, harassment campaigns and cyber attacks, and thus it is not recommended for use.

What is reddit?
Reddit is a social news and entertainment website where registered users can submit content, such as text posts or direct links, in various communities called "subreddits." These subreddits cover a wide range of topics, including news, science, movies, video games, music, books, fitness, food, and image-sharing, among many others.

Users can upvote or downvote content, and the most popular content rises to the top of the subreddit. Reddit also allows users to comment on posts and engage in discussions with other users.

Reddit is known for its diverse and engaged community and its unique voting system that allows users to curate the content they see. The platform is often used for the sharing of news, knowledge, information and the discussion of various topics. It's also a great place for users to find like-minded communities and engage in discussions with people who share similar interests.

However, as with any online community, some individuals may use the platform to spread hate speech, misinformation or engage in harassment, so it is important to be mindful of the content and communities you engage with.

What's your fav Readiohead album.

Before diving into RH, I simply liked Creep, but after hearing other popular songs and eventually OKC, I gradually grew to love the album and the band. Hearing Kid A for the first time, even with how acclaimed it was by critics and fans, I immediately hated it. It was way too far from the sound they built on OKC, and it felt more tiring and boring. Though I was like that with OKC, I don't know what change, but I became more attentive to the album, I stopped focusing on other stuff and really tried to get into the groove

And before you know it... I was grooving like a spastic (insert thom_yorke_dancing.jpg) to Everything In its Right Place, National Anthem (which is probably the most similar to OKC), and Idioteque. But I was also enjoy the space in between the notes and slow mellow vibes on How To Disappear completely, Treefingers.

Currently I only really got into OKC and KA, I've listened to Amnesiac a few months ago and AGAIN I felt it was boring and very slow (but apparently this is a more divisive album on critics and fans). Though I've grown to like some songs, but again Radiohead is a band that demands patience, attention, and somewhat introspection. Once you've clicked with an album or song it's sticks with you

>I seriously fail to comprehend why is this album regarded as a masterpiece?
The problem when listening to classic albums in a modern setting is that neither you, me (or anyone else), well ever TRULY understand the context of which this album was born. We weren't alive to hear and grow up in this period of music, nor did were we around prior to this album and its influence and gradual rise to critical acclaim. I can't say that I feel the way people felt when they listened to this album during its release, like those people who like us, listen to this in a modern setting and can perfectly relate to how people during this album's original release felt.

Anyways here's my quality post for the day
